<h1>State Laws and Regulations in Nigeria</h1>

<p>
Nigeria operates a federal system where powers are shared between the Federal
Government and the 36 States. This page provides a
<strong>detailed, itemised overview of major state laws and regulatory areas</strong>
for educational purposes.
</p>

---

<div class="section">
<h2>1. Laws Common to All States</h2>
<ul>
  <li>State legislation passed by the State House of Assembly</li>
  <li>Land Use and land administration laws</li>
  <li>Environmental sanitation regulations</li>
  <li>Local government administration laws</li>
  <li>Public order and safety regulations</li>
</ul>
</div>

---

<div class="section">
<h2>2. Lagos State – Detailed Laws & Regulations</h2>
<ul>
  <li>Environmental Sanitation Law (waste disposal, street cleanliness)</li>
  <li>Traffic Law enforced by LASTMA</li>
  <li>Tenancy Law regulating rent and landlord–tenant relationships</li>
  <li>Noise Pollution Control Regulations</li>
  <li>Urban and Regional Planning Law</li>
  <li>Street Trading Restrictions</li>
</ul>
</div>

---

<div class="section">
<h2>3. Oil-Producing States (e.g. Rivers, Delta, Bayelsa)</h2>
<ul>
  <li>Environmental protection and pollution control laws</li>
  <li>Community development regulations</li>
  <li>Industrial safety and labour regulations</li>
  <li>Land use laws affecting oil-producing communities</li>
</ul>
</div>

---

<div class="section">
<h2>4. Sharia Law States (Selected States)</h2>
<p>States such as Zamfara, Kano, Sokoto, Katsina, Jigawa, Kebbi, Yobe, Bauchi, Niger and Gombe apply Sharia law alongside federal law.</p>
<ul>
  <li>Family and personal status laws (marriage, divorce, inheritance)</li>
  <li>Restrictions on alcohol consumption and sale</li>
  <li>Morality and public conduct regulations</li>
  <li>Religious court systems for Muslims</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Note:</strong> Sharia law generally applies to Muslims only.</p>
</div>

---

<div class="section">
<h2>5. Security-Focused States (e.g. Borno, Zamfara)</h2>
<ul>
  <li>Emergency regulations and curfews</li>
  <li>Movement restrictions in affected areas</li>
  <li>Public safety and security directives</li>
</ul>
</div>

---

<div class="section">
<h2>6. Cultural & Traditional Laws</h2>
<ul>
  <li>Chieftaincy and traditional leadership laws</li>
  <li>Customary court systems</li>
  <li>Community-based dispute resolution rules</li>
</ul>
</div>

---

<div class="section">
<h2>Important Legal Notes</h2>
<ul>
  <li>State laws differ and may change over time</li>
  <li>Local Government bylaws also apply</li>
  <li>Federal law overrides state law where conflicts exist</li>
</ul>
</div>

